<subSubSection id="C33D651477047F2F81AFA138FE7FFB21" lastPageId="44" lastPageNumber="45" pageId="43" pageNumber="44" type="description">
<paragraph id="8B98369F77047F2881AFA138FDC6F8FA" blockId="43.[151,1072,1723,1823]" box="[151,601,1796,1823]" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">
<figureCitation id="131C2A1A77047F2881AFA138FF6BF8FA" box="[151,244,1796,1822]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="97.[151,250,1713,1737]" captionTargetBox="[180,1408,190,1679]" captionTargetId="figure-19@97.[169,1418,181,1689]" captionTargetPageId="97" captionText="FIGURE 3. Dorsal view of males of: a) Belonuchus magnistylus (paratype), b) B. metafemoralis (paratype), c) B. oxyporimimus (paratype), d) B. pulcher (paratype), e) B. oxyporinus (holotype, NHM©), f) B. oxyporinus, g) B. rufisternus (holotype), h) B. singularis (holotype). Scale bars = 2.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6630887" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6630887/files/figure.png" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">Figs. 3h</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="131C2A1A77047F2881C7A138FEB3F8FA" box="[255,300,1796,1822]" captionStart="FIGURE 10" captionStartId="104.[151,250,1839,1863]" captionTargetBox="[176,1418,194,1806]" captionTargetId="figure-25@104.[152,1435,181,1816]" captionTargetPageId="104" captionText="FIGURE 10. Dorsal view of the head of males of: a) Belonuchus julietitae, b) B. singularis, c) B. connexus, d) B. platypterus, e) B. bidens, f) B. nigerrimus, g) B. optatus, h) B. cyanipennis, i) B. godmani. Dorsal view of the head and pronotum of the holotype female of: j) B. optatus." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6630909" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6630909/files/figure.png" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">10b</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="131C2A1A77047F28800FA138FEE3F8FB" box="[311,380,1796,1823]" captionStart="FIGURE 14" captionStartId="108.[151,250,1944,1968]" captionTargetBox="[185,1402,182,1894]" captionTargetId="figure-25@108.[167,1419,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="108" captionText="FIGURE 14. Dorsal (left) and ventral (right) view of the first four visible abdominal segments of males of: a) Belonuchus singularis, b) B. tepoztecus. Abdominal styli of male of: c) B. alternans, d) B. confusus, e) B. singularis, f) B. magnistylus (right: detail of left stylus in ventral view), g) B. trochanterinus (right: detail of left stylus in ventral view)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6630919" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6630919/files/figure.png" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">14a, e</figureCitation>
, 
<quantity id="4CDF9B7A77047F2880B0A138FE2BF8FA" box="[392,436,1796,1822]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="kg" metricValue="1.7" pageId="43" pageNumber="44" unit="g" value="17.0">17g</quantity>
, 18n, 22e, 26b
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B98369F77047F2881AFA170FEFCF812" blockId="43.[151,1436,1868,2039]" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">
Total body length 
<quantity id="4CDF9B7A77047F288051A170FE4EF883" box="[361,465,1868,1895]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.1199999999999999" pageId="43" pageNumber="44" unit="mm" value="11.2">11.2 mm</quantity>
. The only known specimen might be teneral, thus, what is indicated here as reddishbrown could be black. Reddish-brown on head, antennae, mandibles, neck, pronotum and prosternum. Third and fourth visible abdominal segments irregularly reddish-brown, with some borders lighter. Reddish on maxillary and labial palpi, elytra, scutellum, mesoventrite, metaventrite, legs, visible abdominal segments 1–2 and 5–6, genital segment and styli.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B98369F77037F2F81FFA6ABFC9BFE49" blockId="44.[151,1437,151,1365]" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">
<emphasis id="B953EA8D77037F2F81FFA6ABFE98FF55" bold="true" box="[199,263,151,177]" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">Head</emphasis>
: transverse, ratio length/width 0.62. Dorsal surface with central part of front notably foveate, fovea crossed by sulcate longitudinal midline of head, this later is clearly visible in the fovea and slightly visible backward (
<figureCitation id="131C2A1A77037F2F8198A6E3FE9EFF1E" box="[160,257,223,250]" captionStart="FIGURE 10" captionStartId="104.[151,250,1839,1863]" captionTargetBox="[176,1418,194,1806]" captionTargetId="figure-25@104.[152,1435,181,1816]" captionTargetPageId="104" captionText="FIGURE 10. Dorsal view of the head of males of: a) Belonuchus julietitae, b) B. singularis, c) B. connexus, d) B. platypterus, e) B. bidens, f) B. nigerrimus, g) B. optatus, h) B. cyanipennis, i) B. godmani. Dorsal view of the head and pronotum of the holotype female of: j) B. optatus." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6630909" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6630909/files/figure.png" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">Fig. 10b</figureCitation>
). Eyes slightly more than 0.5 times the cephalic lateral length, slightly protruding at sides. Antennomere 4 elongate, 5 almost as long as wide, 6–10 transverse. Mandibles very long, 1.7 times longer than head; with a basal tooth and a middle tooth, widely separated; mandibular channel well developed, with external margin well separated from internal margin at base, internal margin carinate, extending beyond level of middle tooth. Apical palpomere of maxillary and labial palpi nearly 1.5 times longer than preapical palpomere. Head 1.35 times wider than pronotum. Neck with moderate wrinkled microsculpture ventrally.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B98369F77037F2F81FFA78BFDF8FD15" blockId="44.[151,1437,151,1365]" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">
<emphasis id="B953EA8D77037F2F81FFA78BFEBFFE35" bold="true" box="[199,288,439,465]" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">Thorax</emphasis>
: left dorsal row of pronotum with five punctures and right dorsal row with six punctures; pronotum almost as long as wide (ratio 1.03) and slightly wider at anterior corners than at posterior corners (ratio 1.1). Scutellum with dense punctures, slightly wide and superficial. Elytra with similar punctures as on scutellum, but slightly less dense. Prosternum with an elevated transverse zone near to anterior margin. Intercoxal process of mesoventrite shield-shaped; transverse discal ridge irregular, slightly acute posteriorly. Profemur with external row of spines initiating distant from base and ending distant from apex, spines not dense and of moderate size; internal margin with few spines only near apex. Metatrochanter modified like a hook that is projected until near 1/2 of length of metafemur; metafemur flattened to slightly convex at area of overlap with hook; metatibia curved on internal margin, near midlength. Tarsomeres flattened dorsally.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B98369F77037F2F81FFA4C6FBEBFC2D" blockId="44.[151,1437,151,1365]" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">
<emphasis id="B953EA8D77037F2F81FFA4C6FEA3FCF0" bold="true" box="[199,316,762,788]" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">Abdomen</emphasis>
: first visible tergite with posterior basal transverse carina well developed, visible tergites 2–3 with posterior basal transverse carina somewhat faint; depressed adjacent zone well developed, with dense wide-superficial punctures; remaining parts of abdomen only with fine, moderately dense punctures (
<figureCitation id="131C2A1A77037F2F8540A57FFB47FCB9" box="[1144,1240,835,861]" captionStart="FIGURE 14" captionStartId="108.[151,250,1944,1968]" captionTargetBox="[185,1402,182,1894]" captionTargetId="figure-25@108.[167,1419,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="108" captionText="FIGURE 14. Dorsal (left) and ventral (right) view of the first four visible abdominal segments of males of: a) Belonuchus singularis, b) B. tepoztecus. Abdominal styli of male of: c) B. alternans, d) B. confusus, e) B. singularis, f) B. magnistylus (right: detail of left stylus in ventral view), g) B. trochanterinus (right: detail of left stylus in ventral view)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6630919" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6630919/files/figure.png" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">Fig. 14a</figureCitation>
). Male pregenital sternite with distinct V-shaped emargination at posterior margin (Fig. 
<quantity id="4CDF9B7A77037F2F8294A55BFC45FC65" box="[940,986,871,897]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="kg" metricValue="1.7" pageId="44" pageNumber="45" unit="g" value="17.0">17g</quantity>
). Male genital sternite short (2.33 times longer than wide), moderately asymmetrical, anterior portion occupying 40% and posterior portion 60% of its length, apical emargination deep and wide (
<figureCitation id="131C2A1A77037F2F83B8A593FD7DFC2D" box="[640,738,943,969]" captionStart="FIGURE 18" captionStartId="112.[151,250,1799,1823]" captionTargetBox="[174,1411,182,1767]" captionTargetId="figure-25@112.[173,1413,181,1775]" captionTargetPageId="112" captionText="FIGURE 18. Male genital sternite of: a) Belonuchus altenans, b) B. apiciventris, c) B. cariniventris, d) B. colon, e) B. confusus, f) B. julietitae, g) B. magnistylus, h) B. linuzensis, i) B. metafemoralis, j) B. oxyporimimus, k) B. oxyporinus, l) B. pulcher, m) B. rufisternus, n) B. singularis, o) B. tenuistylus. Scale bars = 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6630925" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6630925/files/figure.png" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">Fig. 18n</figureCitation>
). Abdominal styli moderately wide.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B98369F77037F2F81FFA5EEFA11FBF5" blockId="44.[151,1437,151,1365]" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">
<emphasis id="B953EA8D77037F2F81FFA5EEFEDBFC08" bold="true" box="[199,324,978,1004]" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">Aedeagus:</emphasis>
length 
<quantity id="4CDF9B7A77037F2F80AFA5EFFE6FFC09" box="[407,496,979,1005]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.6" pageId="44" pageNumber="45" unit="mm" value="1.6">1.6 mm</quantity>
; elongate shape; apex wide and convex, sides slightly narrowed in anterior third and then gradually widened towards base; basal half moderately wider than apical half; internal sac visible (
<figureCitation id="131C2A1A77037F2F8419A5CBFA1EFBF5" box="[1313,1409,1015,1041]" captionStart="FIGURE 22" captionStartId="116.[151,250,1894,1918]" captionTargetBox="[162,1427,182,1859]" captionTargetId="figure-25@116.[151,1436,181,1871]" captionTargetPageId="116" captionText="FIGURE 22. Ventral (left) and lateral (right) view of the aedeagus of: a) Belonuchus oxyporimimus, b) B. oxyporinus, c) B. pulcher, d) B. rufisternus, e) B. singularis, f) B. tenuistylus, g) B. tepoztecus (at center detail of the paramere), h) B. trochanterinus, i) B. zunilensis. Scale bar = 0.5 mm (all figures)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6630937" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6630937/files/figure.png" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">Fig. 22e</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B98369F77037F2F81FFA226FB83FBD1" blockId="44.[151,1437,151,1365]" box="[199,1052,1050,1077]" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">
<emphasis id="B953EA8D77037F2F81FFA226FED8FBD0" bold="true" box="[199,327,1050,1076]" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">Variability</emphasis>
. Could not be assessed due to availability of only 
<specimenCount id="9D21FD1677037F2F8243A227FB87FBD1" box="[891,1048,1051,1077]" pageId="44" pageNumber="45" type="generic">one specimen</specimenCount>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B98369F77037F2F81FFA202FE7FFB21" blockId="44.[151,1437,151,1365]" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">
<emphasis id="B953EA8D77037F2F81FFA202FE54FBBD" bold="true" box="[199,459,1086,1113]" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">Taxonomic comments</emphasis>
. Due the color pattern of the abdomen, combining reddish and dark-reddish segments, this species resembles some species of 
<taxonomicName id="4C274D1C77037F2F8362A25FFC9EFB99" authorityName="Sharp" authorityYear="1885" box="[602,769,1123,1149]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Paederomimus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="44" pageNumber="45" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B953EA8D77037F2F8362A25FFC9EFB99" box="[602,769,1123,1149]" italics="true" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">Paederomimus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. This is the only Mexican species of 
<taxonomicName id="4C274D1C77037F2F858BA25FFAA9FB99" box="[1203,1334,1123,1149]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Belonuchus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="44" pageNumber="45" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B953EA8D77037F2F858BA25FFAA9FB99" box="[1203,1334,1123,1149]" italics="true" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">Belonuchus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with the third and fourth visible abdominal segments dark and fifth and sixth segments pale, all the other species with dark segments have them apically.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C33D651477037F2F81FFA2F3FA9AFB0D" box="[199,1285,1231,1257]" pageId="44" pageNumber="45" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="8B98369F77037F2F81FFA2F3FA9AFB0D" blockId="44.[151,1437,151,1365]" box="[199,1285,1231,1257]" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">
<emphasis id="B953EA8D77037F2F81FFA2F3FED1FB0D" bold="true" box="[199,334,1231,1257]" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">Etymology.</emphasis>
The name refers to the fact that only a single specimen of this species was available.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C33D651477037F2F81FFA2CFFED5FAB1" pageId="44" pageNumber="45" type="materials_examined">
<paragraph id="8B98369F77037F2F81FFA2CFFED5FAB1" blockId="44.[151,1437,151,1365]" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">
<emphasis id="B953EA8D77037F2F81FFA2CFFEE5FAE8" bold="true" box="[199,378,1266,1293]" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">Type material:</emphasis>
<materialsCitation id="3B4F3CC277037F2F80BBA2CFFED5FAB1" collectingDate="1971-07-22" collectingDateMax="1971-07-31" collectingDateMin="1971-07-22" collectionCode="FMNH" collectorName="A. Newton" country="Mexico" determinerName="Newton" elevation="975" location="Valle Nacional" pageId="44" pageNumber="45" specimenCount="1" stateProvince="Oaxaca" typeStatus="holotype">
<emphasis id="B953EA8D77037F2F80BBA2CFFE6FFAE9" bold="true" box="[387,496,1267,1293]" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">
<typeStatus id="549C883D77037F2F80BBA2CFFE6FFAE9" box="[387,496,1267,1293]" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">Holotype</typeStatus>
